[2]
Date: 10 Dec 2005
From: Pablo Nart <pablo12@hotPOP.com>
Source: TurkishPress, 8 Dec 2005 [edited]
<http://www.turkishpress.com/news.asp?id=85067>

Thousands of beef cattle are being destroyed in Minnesota as authorities
try to stop the first outbreak of bovine tuberculosis in the northwestern
US state in 34 years.
The United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) is set to strip
Minnesota of its bovine-TB free status, making it the 4th US state bumped
from the roster alongside Michigan, Texas and New Mexico.
Agriculture officials stressed that this is not a human health threat and
so was unlikely to affect trade.
US cattle are routinely checked for TB before they are exported. Minnesota
exports small numbers of live cattle to countries such as China and Cuba,
but generally not to Europe.
The outbreak, with nearly 5000 head of Minnesota cattle destroyed or soon
to be destroyed, comes as US farmers anticipate Japan reopening its borders
to US beef within days, following a mad-cow scare.
Since discovering a case of bovine TB in a cow from Roseau County, near the
Canadian frontier in February 2005, Minnesota officials have moved quickly
to detect and contain the disease, so far quarantining 42 herds. 10 remain
quarantined.
On Wednesday, the last of 3080 head of cattle in 4 herds were destroyed in
Roseau County. Another 1000 head in Beltrami County in northwestern
Minnesota are also set to be destroyed.
Officials say consumers have little risk of catching the respiratory
illness. But farmers will be required to pay for mandatory testing of any
cattle that are to be shipped out of state for breeding or to feedlots.
Now, animal-health officials in a half dozen other states are tracing
exposures that their cattle may have had with tuberculin cattle in
Minnesota. "I don't think tuberculosis is going to be very widespread in
the United States," said Kevin Elfering, director of the dairy and food
inspection division of the Minnesota Agriculture Department. "I think there
are going to be isolated cases."
Meanwhile, consumers have little to worry about, unless they drink
unpasteurized milk, eat under-cooked beef, or rub noses with a cow,
officials said.
In Michigan, white-tailed deer are blamed for an outbreak that cost farmers
an estimated 156 million dollars in lost cattle sales in the past decade.
Regaining TB-free status is not easy for states that have had the disease.
It generally takes 2 years once a state finds no more TB cases to be deemed
disease-free.
